<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1615,2038]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,328,1615,1642]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Behaviour.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Skowron Volponi, 2019" authorityName="Skowron Volponi" authorityYear="2019" box="[337,440,1616,1642]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Melanosphecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paolo" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[337,440,1616,1642]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">M. paolo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[448,539,1616,1642]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[448,539,1616,1642]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
was found mud-puddling (
<emphasis bold="true" box="[851,1001,1615,1642]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Suppl. video</emphasis>
: time code 00:23–02:12), a behaviour of sucking up liquids from moist substrate recently observed for a number of Oriental 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Boisduval" authorityYear="1828" box="[1135,1228,1652,1678]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Sesiidae</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Gorbunov" box="[1244,1431,1651,1678]" firstAuthor="Gorbunov" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" pagination="98 - 100" refId="ref3405" refString="Gorbunov, O. (2015) Scientific note: Clearwing moths (Lepidoptera: Sesiidae) of Laos. I. Akaisphecia melanopuncta O. Gorbunov &amp; Arita, 1995 (Sesiidae: Sesiinae: Osminiini). Tropical Lepidoptera Research, 25 (2), 98 - 100." type="journal article" year="2015">Gorbunov, 2015</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Quicke" box="[151,369,1688,1714]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Quicke" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" pagination="490 - 492" refId="ref3771" refString="Quicke, D. L. J., Skowron Volponi, M. A., Kitching, I. J., Butcher, B. A. &amp; Giudici, A. (2018) Scientific Note: First record of the remarkable clearwing moth, Akaisphecia melanopuncta O. Gorbunov &amp; Arita, 1995 (Sesiidae: Sesiinae: Osminiini), from Thailand, with comments on likely Batesian mimicry. J Asia-Pacific Entomology, 21 (2), 490 - 492. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. aspen. 2018.02.002" type="journal article" year="2018">
Quicke 
<emphasis box="[239,289,1688,1714]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">et al</emphasis>
., 2018
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Skowron" box="[382,620,1687,1714]" etAl="et al." firstAuthor="Skowron" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" pagination="426 - 434" refId="ref4225" refString="Skowron, M. A., Munisamy, B., Hamid, S. B. A. &amp; Wegrzyn, G. (2015) A new species of clearwing moth (Lepidoptera: Sesiidae: Osminiini) from Peninsular Malaysia, exhibiting bee-like morphology and behaviour. Zootaxa, 4032 (4), 426 - 434. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4032.4.7" type="journal article" year="2015">
Skowron 
<emphasis box="[490,540,1688,1714]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">et al</emphasis>
., 2015
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Skowron Volponi &amp; Volponi" box="[632,1026,1688,1714]" firstAuthor="Skowron Volponi" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" pagination="129 - 139" refId="ref4363" refString="Skowron Volponi, M. A. &amp; Volponi, P. (2017) A new species of wasp-mimicking clearwing moth from Peninsular Malaysia with DNA barcode and behavioural notes (Lepidoptera, Sesiidae). ZooKeys, 692, 129 - 139. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 692.13587" type="journal article" year="2017">Skowron Volponi &amp; Volponi, 2017</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="Quicke, D. L. J. &amp; Skowron Volponi, M. A. &amp; Kitching, I. J. &amp; Butcher, B. A. &amp; Giudici, A." box="[1037,1097,1688,1714]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" pagination="490 - 492" refId="ref3771" refString="Quicke, D. L. J., Skowron Volponi, M. A., Kitching, I. J., Butcher, B. A. &amp; Giudici, A. (2018) Scientific Note: First record of the remarkable clearwing moth, Akaisphecia melanopuncta O. Gorbunov &amp; Arita, 1995 (Sesiidae: Sesiinae: Osminiini), from Thailand, with comments on likely Batesian mimicry. J Asia-Pacific Entomology, 21 (2), 490 - 492. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / j. aspen. 2018.02.002" type="journal article" year="2018">2018</bibRefCitation>
), on a river bank. It landed on moist rocks, sometimes surrounded by algae (
<figureCitation box="[674,741,1724,1750]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,250,1797,1822]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,877,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1435,877,1777]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURE 1 Melanosphecia paolo Skowron Volponi sp. nov., two individuals mud-puddling, in 2017 (top left) and 2019. Photographs taken by Marta Skowron Volponi &amp; Paolo Volponi." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3532635" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3532635/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). When puddling, it would fly from one rock to another in a rugged flight (Suppl. video TC 02:41–03:00), in a similar manner to 
<taxonomicName box="[923,1051,1760,1786]" class="Insecta" family="Pompilidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Pompilidae</taxonomicName>
wasps approaching their burrows. It was observed ejecting excess water during puddling, which indicates it is puddling for salt or other minerals and not just for the moisture. In flight, the sesiid arches its abdomen which gives it an even more pompilid wasp-like appearance (Suppl. video: TC 03:01–03:43). This clearwing moth actively uses the long hind legs for locomotion or to cling on to a rock during puddling (Suppl. video: TC 01:51–02:12), in contrast to, for example, 
<taxonomicName authority="Skowron, 2015" authorityName="Skowron" authorityYear="2015" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Heterosphecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pahangensis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">Heterosphecia pahangensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Skowron" box="[298,469,1939,1966]" firstAuthor="Skowron" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" pagination="426 - 434" refId="ref4225" refString="Skowron, M. A., Munisamy, B., Hamid, S. B. A. &amp; Wegrzyn, G. (2015) A new species of clearwing moth (Lepidoptera: Sesiidae: Osminiini) from Peninsular Malaysia, exhibiting bee-like morphology and behaviour. Zootaxa, 4032 (4), 426 - 434. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4032.4.7" type="journal article" year="2015">Skowron, 2015</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(a species also belonging to the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duckworth &amp; Eichlin" authorityYear="1977" box="[833,945,1940,1966]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="298" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Osminiini">Osminiini</taxonomicName>
tribe), whose hind legs are dysfunctional in terms of locomotion. It rests with its wings folded back against its body.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1437,1615,2038]" lastBlockId="4.[151,1437,152,466]" lastPageId="4" lastPageNumber="299" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,473,2011,2038]" pageId="3" pageNumber="298">DNA barcode analysis.</emphasis>
A 648 bp fragment of the mitochondrial cytochrome c oxidase subunit I gene (COI) was sequenced (GenBank accession number 
<accessionNumber box="[660,790,152,179]" httpUri="http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nucleotide/MN514946" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">MN514946</accessionNumber>
) and it confirmed placement of 
<taxonomicName authority="Skowron Volponi, 2019" authorityName="Skowron Volponi" authorityYear="2019" box="[1156,1258,152,178]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Melanosphecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paolo" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[1156,1258,152,178]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">M. paolo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1266,1357,153,179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1266,1357,153,179]" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
within the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Duckworth &amp; Eichlin" authorityYear="1977" box="[193,305,188,214]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Osminiini">Osminiini</taxonomicName>
tribe, however no other species of the 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Le Cerf" authorityYear="1916" box="[748,919,188,214]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Melanosphecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[748,919,188,214]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">Melanosphecia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
genus have been barcoded to date, thus comparisons were not feasible. From published records, the 
<taxonomicName authority="Skowron Volponi, 2019" authorityName="Skowron Volponi" authorityYear="2019" box="[785,887,224,250]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Melanosphecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="paolo" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[785,887,224,250]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">M. paolo</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[895,985,225,251]" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[895,985,225,251]" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
COI sequence revealed highest identity with 
<taxonomicName authority="Skowron" authorityName="Skowron" authorityYear="2015" box="[208,625,260,286]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Heterosphecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pahangensis">
<emphasis box="[208,517,260,286]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">Heterosphecia pahangensis</emphasis>
Skowron
</taxonomicName>
(8.4% divergence), 
<taxonomicName authority="Arita &amp; Gorbunov" authorityName="Arita &amp; Gorbunov" box="[852,1224,260,287]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Heterosphecia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bantanakai">
<emphasis box="[852,1012,260,286]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">H. bantanakai</emphasis>
Arita &amp; Gorbunov
</taxonomicName>
(10% divergence), 
<taxonomicName authority="Skowron Volponi, 2017" authorityName="Skowron Volponi" authorityYear="2017" box="[151,628,296,323]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Pyrophleps" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ellawi">
<emphasis box="[151,353,296,322]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">Pyrophleps ellawi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Skowron Volponi" box="[361,628,296,323]" firstAuthor="Skowron Volponi" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" pagination="129 - 139" refId="ref4363" refString="Skowron Volponi, M. A. &amp; Volponi, P. (2017) A new species of wasp-mimicking clearwing moth from Peninsular Malaysia with DNA barcode and behavioural notes (Lepidoptera, Sesiidae). ZooKeys, 692, 129 - 139. https: // doi. org / 10.3897 / zookeys. 692.13587" type="journal article" year="2017">Skowron Volponi, 2017</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(10.3% divergence) and 
<taxonomicName authority="Arita &amp; Gorbunov" authorityName="Arita &amp; Gorbunov" box="[912,1275,296,323]" class="Insecta" family="Sesiidae" genus="Pyrophleps" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="299" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vitripennis">
<emphasis box="[912,1060,297,322]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="299">P. vitripennis</emphasis>
Arita &amp; Gorbunov
</taxonomicName>
(11.1% divergence).
</paragraph>
